. We can use category. But allowed tokens: state, state_abbr. Borough could be state abbreviation? Not accurate. Use category.\n\nX Coordinate (State Plane): unknown numeric coordinate; maybe latitude? No, it's state plane coordinate. So content_type unknown.\n\nY Coordinate (State Plane): unknown.\n\nOpen Data Channel Type: category.\n\nPark Facility Name: free_text or category? It's name of park facility, treat as free_text.\n\nPark Borough: category.\n\nVehicle Type: category.\n\nTaxi Company Borough: category.\n\nTaxi Pick Up Location: free_text.\n\nBridge Highway Name: free_text? Category maybe. Use free_text or category; choose category.\n\nBridge Highway Direction: category.\n\nRoad Ramp: category.\n\nBridge Highway Segment: free_text? Category? Use category.\n\nLatitude: latitude.\n\nLongitude: longitude.\n\nLocation: free_text (coordinate string). Could be coordinate pair string; use free_text.\n\nNow produce JSON with all 41 fields. Ensure each field name matches exactly as in list, e.g., \"Unique Key\", \"Created Date\" etc.\n\nWe need label human-friendly same as original? Provide similar but maybe more descriptive. Description: include context from dataset description using freq distribution. We'll craft concise descriptions referencing dataset.\n\nLet's generate.\n\n\n\nREFINE PASS REASONING:\nWe need to refine the first-pass dictionary adding cross-field relationships. We must output JSON with keys being field names? In first pass, fields array; but requested output format: same shape as first pass? Actually final instruction: \"Return the results in the SAME JSON shape as the first pass:\" then example shows mapping of field_name_1 to dict. That means we need an object where each key is field name string (not an array). So produce top-level keys with field names.\n\nNeed to adjust labels, descriptions, content_type for all fields. For those belonging to composite concept: mailing address components, etc.\n\nWe should identify groups:\n\nMailing address:\n- Incident Address (street address)\n- Street Name\n- Cross Street 1\n- Cross Street 2\n- Intersection Street 1\n- Intersection Street 2\n- City\n- Incident Zip\n- Address Type maybe indicates type of address.\n\nAlso there is Location field as lat/long string.\n\nGeographic coordinate:\n- Latitude, Longitude, plus combined? Not needed.\n\nTime ranges: Created Date, Closed Date, Due Date, Resolution Action Updated Date. Might group as timestamps but not composite.\n\nResolution description separate.\n\nAgency etc.\n\nVehicle type etc.\n\nPark Facility Name and Park Borough maybe related.\n\nTaxi fields.\n\nBridge Highway fields.\n\nBBL, Community Board, Borough, City, etc.\n\nWe must refine labels: e.g., \"Incident Address\" label stays same? But maybe \"Street address (incident location)\".\n\nBetter to add cross-field context in description.\n\nContent types: We need adjust some:\n\n- Unique Key: content_type omitted. So no key for that field.\n\n- Created Date: datetime:%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p? The sample values like \"01/24/2013 12:00:00 AM\" so format \"%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\". Good.\n\n- Closed Date: same format, but some nulls. Use datetime:%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p.\n\n- Agency: company_name okay.\n\n- Agency Name: company_name.\n\n- Complaint Type: category maybe fine.\n\n- Descriptor: free_text.\n\n- Location Type: category.\n\n- Incident Zip: zip_code.\n\n- Incident Address: street_address. (content_type changed)\n\n- Street Name: street_name.\n\n- Cross Street 1/2: street_name? Might be free_text but better as street_name.\n\n- Intersection Street 1/2: street_name.\n\n- Address Type: category (maybe address_type but not in vocab). Keep category.\n\n- City: city.\n\n- Landmark: free_text.\n\n- Facility Type: category.\n\n- Status: category.\n\n- Due Date: datetime:%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\n\n- Resolution Description: free_text.\n\n- Resolution Action Updated Date: datetime:%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\n\n- Community Board: category.\n\n- BBL: uuid? It's numeric but unique identifier for parcel. Might be uuid type (but numeric). Could use uuid or unknown. Keep uuid maybe.\n\n- Borough: state_abbr? Actually borough names. Use category or state_abbr? But boroughs are not states. So keep category.\n\n- X Coordinate (State Plane): unknown? Maybe integer but no vocab; keep unknown.\n\n- Y Coordinate (State Plane): unknown.\n\n- Open Data Channel Type: category.\n\n- Park Facility Name: free_text.\n\n- Park Borough: category.\n\n- Vehicle Type: category.\n\n- Taxi Company Borough: category.\n\n- Taxi Pick Up Location: free_text.\n\n- Bridge Highway Name: free_text? Could be street_name but maybe free_text. Keep free_text.\n\n- Bridge Highway Direction: category.\n\n- Road Ramp: category.\n\n- Bridge Highway Segment: free_text.\n\n- Latitude: latitude.\n\n- Longitude: longitude.\n\n- Location: free_text (string of lat/long). Might keep free_text.\n\nAlso we might remove content_type for Unique Key and maybe BBL? But first pass gave uuid. We can leave.\n\nNow refine descriptions:\n\nAdd cross-field context: e.g., Incident Address: \"Street address of the incident location; combine with City, Incident Zip, and Address Type to form full address.\" etc.\n\nStreet Name: \"Primary street name at the incident location; part of the mailing address.\"\n\nCross Street 1/2: \"First/second cross street intersecting at incident location; used for intersection-based addresses.\"\n\nIntersection Street 1/2: same.\n\nCity: \"Borough or city where the incident occurred; may match Borough field but provides full name.\" etc.\n\nLatitude/Longitude: specify decimal degrees.\n\nLocation: \"String representation of latitude and longitude, e.g., (40.1234, -73.5678); redundant with Latitude and Longitude fields.\"\n\nBBL: \"Unique identifier for a parcel in NYC, composed of borough-block-lot numbers; use with Community Board and Borough to locate property.\" etc.\n\nPark Facility Name/Borough: refer to park location.\n\nBridge Highway fields: provide context.\n\nNow produce JSON mapping. Need to include all 41 fields except Unique Key? Actually must output field_name_1 mapping. Should we include Unique Key? We need to omit content_type key but still provide label and description? The instruction says for unique_id, omit content_type key entirely; not that we omit the field. So keep Unique Key with label and description but no content_type.\n\nAlso note: For fields where first-pass content type is unknown or free_text etc but we changed to something else, we must include new content_type.\n\nLet's craft JSON object.\n\nCheck that all keys are valid JSON property names; they may contain spaces? In example they use field_name_1. We need keys exactly as field names with spaces? The instruction: \"field_name_1\" placeholder. So we should use actual field names but maybe need to escape spaces? JSON allows string keys with spaces if quoted. Example shows mapping of \"field_name_1\". So we can use the field name as key.\n\nWe'll produce:\n\n{\n  \"Unique Key\": { \"label\":\"Unique Key\", \"description\":\"A system-generated integer that uniquely identifies each record in the dataset.\" },\n  \"Created Date\": { ... content_type: \"datetime:%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\" },\n  ...\n}\n\nOk.\n\nLet's produce all fields."
