Description:
  response: "**Description**\n\nThe dataset contains one million anonymized NYC 311 service‑request records collected between January 2010 and December 2020. Each record is uniquely identified by an integer key and includes timestamps for when the request was created, closed, or last updated, as well as a wide range of categorical descriptors such as agency, complaint type, location details, and resolution narrative. The majority of requests (≈ 95 %) are still open or pending, with only about 15 % having a recorded close date. Geographical information is available for roughly three‑quarters of the records via latitude/longitude pairs or state‑plane coordinates, while many address‑related fields remain missing.\n\n**Notable Characteristics**\n\n- **Temporal distribution** – Creation dates cluster around early‑mid 2013–2014 with a slight left‑skew (-0.017), reflecting increased reporting activity during that period.\n- **Missing data** – Large proportions of key fields are null: ~25 % for latitude/longitude, 64 % for due date, and 2.9 % for closed date; address components (Incident Address, Street Name) have up to 36 % nulls.\n- **Open‑ended categories** – The “Other” bucket dominates several categorical fields: ~56 % of complaint types, ~67 % of descriptors, and ~8 % of agency codes are classified as “Other”.\n- **Geospatial spread** – Latitude ranges from 40.112° to 40.913°, longitude from –77.520° to –73.701°, covering all five boroughs; state‑plane coordinates span roughly 900 k–1 100 k (X) and 120 k–270 k (Y), with a dense cluster around Manhattan.\n- **Duplicates** – The unique key guarantees no duplicate records; cardinality equals the number of rows.\n- **Outliers & anomalies** – Closed dates extend from 1900 to 2100, but the vast majority fall between 2010 and 2020. A few extremely high X/Y coordinates correspond to “Other (N)” groups in frequency tables, indicating aggregated outlier locations.\n- **Data quality** – High skewness in several fields indicates heavy‑tailed distributions; many categorical values have low cardinality thresholds, suggesting potential for further aggregation or mapping.\n- **PII/PHI considerations** – While the dataset includes addresses and precise coordinates, it does not contain personally identifying information such as names or contact details. Nevertheless, location data may be sensitive for privacy compliance.\n\n**Attribution**\n\nGenerated by qsv v20.1.0 describegpt\nCommand line: target/debug/qsv describegpt --all --two-pass /tmp/NYC_311_SR_2010-2020-sample-1M.csv -o /tmp/nyc311-describegpt.toon --infer-content-type --format toon\nPrompt file: Default v7.1.0\nModel: openai/gpt-oss-20b\nLLM API URL: http://localhost:1234/v1\nLanguage: \nTimestamp: 2026-05-22T02:20:14.141012+00:00\n\nWARNING: Description generated by an LLM and may contain inaccuracies. Verify before using!\n"
